The Prime Minister Narendra Modi didn’t say a single word regarding the Kashmir issue during his speech at the United Nations Assembly today
The 74th session of the United Nations Assembly is currently in progress.
Prime Minister Narendra Modi spoke on behalf of India today.
During his speech he called on the nations of the world to unite against terrorism.
During his speech he quoted lines of the Tamil poet Kaniyan Poonkundranar “The world is one, all are relations.”
Modi proudly said that the contribution of India in global warming is moving towards a solution, and said that India is contributing less to global warming and giving more solutions.
The government of India is taking serious initiatives to make India free of plastics.
He also said that a large scale health insurance plan is being implemented in India.
Modi quoted the nice lines ‘World is one, all are relation’ in Tamil.
But he did not refer to Jammu Kashmir at any point during his speech.
The reason for this is the strong determination of the central government that Jammu Kashmir is an internal problem of India.
With Pakistan wishing to make it an international issue, Modi has intentionally avoided any words about Jammu Kashmir, say political observers.
This has sent a message to the countries of the world that Kashmir is an internal issue of India.
In a literacy test conducted in Kerala, 2,993 tribal people have passed.
An 85 year old elderly woman has also passed in this exam.
As per the 2011 census, 93.91% of the people in Kerala are literate.
Kerala government is taking efforts to make it 100%.
The State Literacy commission was formed for this purpose.
This commission is conducting classes and exams in each district to increase literacy.
Importantly, this commission is taking serious steps to provide literacy to tribal people, fishermen and migrant workers.
Classes for providing literacy to the tribal dominated area in Vayanad district were conducted from last February and exams were conducted recently.
This exam was conducted for 100 marks; 30 marks were allotted for competency in reading, 40 marks for writing competency, and 30 marks for knowledge in mathematics.
It is compulsory to score 30 marks for a pass in this exam.
3,090 tribal people from Vayanad district took part in the exam.
The literacy commission has announced that 2,993 of them have passed.
This includes an 85 year old woman.
The Director of School Education, S.Kannappan has ordered the distribution of second term books and notebooks for students studying in 27 government and government-aided schools on October 3.
He sent out a circular regarding this, to the Chief Educational Officers and District Educational Officers of all districts on Wednesday:
Free notebooks for government and government-aided schools are given to all districts through TNPL.
Similarly, free books for the second term were sent through the Tamil Nadu textbook society.
Chief Educational Officers of all districts have to distribute books and notebooks for all government and government-aided schools in their districts before September 30.
In his circular, he also asked them to instruct all headmasters to distribute the free books and notebooks on the first day of term, after quarterly exams.
